properties.name: <![CDATA[St Rhidian and St Illtyd's Church, Llanrhidian]]>
<![CDATA[St Cennydd’s Church, Llangennith]]>
properties.cmt: <![CDATA[The Church the largest in Gower - which was founded in the 6th century, in the days of the undivided Church. According to legend the church was established as a hermitage by St Cenydd; but in 986 the early buildings were destroyed by Vikings. The present structure dates from the 12th century - it was consecrated in 1102 - when Norman war-lords were building castles and churches all over Gower.]]>

properties.name: <![CDATA[Llangenith Holy Well]]>
properties.cmt: <![CDATA[St Cenydd's Holy WellJust opposite the lytch gate (the only one in the Gower) a small spring gushes forth, protected by a stone well-head. The spring is one of several in the area connected to legends of St Cenydd. It is said that the water sprang forth when Cenydd struck his staff on the earth, and like many holy wells the water is said to have healing qualities. I don't know about the healing qualities, but I can tell you from personal experience that the water tastes clear, clean, and cold!"]]>
